@* ERROR BOUNDARY (decision 164). <ErrorBoundary> shows ErrorContent instead of its ChildContent
   once the content has thrown, and leaves everything OUTSIDE it mounted and live.

   WHAT IT CATCHES WAS MEASURED, NOT ASSUMED, against this very framework build — the catch lives in
   Renderer.HandleExceptionViaErrorBoundary, which is ordinary .NET, so tools/error-boundary-oracle
   drives it headless and reports:

     W1  a throw from an event handler the PARENT owns, written inside the boundary   NOT caught
     W2  a throw from a CHILD COMPONENT's event handler                                   caught
     W3  a throw from a CHILD COMPONENT's OnInitialized                                    caught
     W4  a throw raised while the parent EVALUATES the content                             caught

   W1 is the shape everyone expects and Blazor does NOT catch it: a boundary catches what its
   DESCENDANTS raise, and a handler written in the boundary's child content belongs to the component
   that WROTE the fragment — an ancestor. W2/W3 need a stateful child, which Filament's composition
   subset refuses. So W4 is the case this baseline pins, because it is the one both sides can reach.

   The lowering: everything inlines into one mount(), so no boundary component survives. What
   remains is a `signal(null)` latch — null IS CurrentException — and ONE list() over a comment
   anchor whose active key set is the content while the latch is null and the error UI after, which
   is @if/@else's own shape. Zero new runtime primitives.

   DOM contract: Risky() throws while the content is being evaluated, so #in is NEVER rendered;
   #err carries the caught message, and #outside stays mounted. That is the measurement. *@

<div id="wrap"><p id="outside">outside</p><ErrorBoundary><ChildContent><p id="in">@Risky()</p></ChildContent><ErrorContent><p id="err">Sorry: @context.Message</p></ErrorContent></ErrorBoundary></div>

@code {
    private bool fail = true;

    private string Risky()
    {
        if (fail) throw new InvalidOperationException("the content could not be rendered");
        return "ok";
    }
}
